{
  "id": "taittiriya",
  "name": "Taittiriya Upanishad",
  "name_sanskrit": "तैत्तिरीयोपनिषद्",
  "tradition": "Krishna Yajurveda",
  "summary": "The Taittiriya Upanishad has three sections: Shiksha Valli (on phonetics and ethics), Brahmananda Valli (on the five sheaths and Brahman as bliss), and Bhrigu Valli (Bhrigu's progressive discovery of Brahman). It famously declares: satyam jnanam anantam brahma — Brahman is truth, knowledge, infinity.",
  "total_verses": 81,
  "verses": [
    {
      "upanishad": "taittiriya",
      "verse_number": 1,
      "tags": [
        "Brahman",
        "truth",
        "knowledge",
        "infinity"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "सत्यं ज्ञानमनन्तं ब्रह्म | यो वेद निहितं गुहायां परमे व्योमन् |\nसोऽश्नुते सर्वान् कामान् सह | ब्रह्मणा विपश्चितेति ||२.१.१||",
      "transliteration": "satyaṃ jñānam anantaṃ brahma | yo veda nihitaṃ guhāyāṃ parame vyoman |\nso'śnute sarvān kāmān saha | brahmaṇā vipaściteti ||2.1.1||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "सत्यम्",
          "meaning": "truth, existence"
        },
        {
          "word": "ज्ञानम्",
          "meaning": "knowledge, consciousness"
        },
        {
          "word": "अनन्तम्",
          "meaning": "infinite, endless"
        },
        {
          "word": "ब्रह्म",
          "meaning": "Brahman"
        },
        {
          "word": "गुहायाम् निहितम्",
          "meaning": "hidden in the cave (of the heart)"
        },
        {
          "word": "सर्वान् कामान् अश्नुते",
          "meaning": "attains all desires"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "Brahman is truth, knowledge, infinity. One who knows it hidden in the cave of the heart, in the highest ether, attains all desires together with the all-knowing Brahman.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "सत्यम् — परिणामरहितम्। ज्ञानम् — चैतन्यस्वरूपम्। अनन्तम् — देशकालवस्तुपरिच्छेदरहितम्। एतत् ब्रह्म।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: Satyam — that which does not undergo transformation. Jnanam — whose very nature is consciousness. Anantam — unlimited by space, time, or object. This is Brahman. One who knows this hidden in the heart attains all."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "taittiriya",
      "verse_number": 2,
      "tags": [
        "five sheaths",
        "annamaya",
        "pranamaya",
        "manomaya"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "अन्नमयो ह्येवायं पुरुषः | तस्येदमेव शिरः | अयं दक्षिणः पक्षः | अयमुत्तरः पक्षः | अयमात्मा | इदं पुच्छं प्रतिष्ठा ||२.१.२||",
      "transliteration": "annamayo hy evāyaṃ puruṣaḥ | tasyedam eva śiraḥ | ayaṃ dakṣiṇaḥ pakṣaḥ | ayam uttaraḥ pakṣaḥ | ayam ātmā | idaṃ pucchaṃ pratiṣṭhā ||2.1.2||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "अन्नमयः पुरुषः",
          "meaning": "the person made of food"
        },
        {
          "word": "शिरः",
          "meaning": "head"
        },
        {
          "word": "दक्षिणः पक्षः",
          "meaning": "right wing/side"
        },
        {
          "word": "उत्तरः पक्षः",
          "meaning": "left wing/side"
        },
        {
          "word": "आत्मा",
          "meaning": "trunk/body"
        },
        {
          "word": "पुच्छम् प्रतिष्ठा",
          "meaning": "tail, the foundation"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "This person is indeed made of the essence of food. This is his head, this his right wing, this his left wing, this his trunk, this his tail — the foundation.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "अन्नमयः — अन्नरसपरिणामः स्थूलशरीरम्। पञ्चकोशानां मध्ये बाह्यतमः कोशः।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The annamaya kosha (food sheath) is the gross body, a transformation of the essence of food. It is the outermost of the five sheaths. The teaching progressively moves inward to discover the true Self beyond all sheaths."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "taittiriya",
      "verse_number": 3,
      "tags": [
        "ananda",
        "bliss",
        "Brahman",
        "joy"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "आनन्दो ब्रह्मेति व्यजानात् | आनन्दाद्ध्येव खल्विमानि भूतानि जायन्ते |\nआनन्देन जातानि जीवन्ति | आनन्दं प्रयन्त्यभिसंविशन्तीति ||३.६.१||",
      "transliteration": "ānando brahmeti vyajānāt | ānandād dhy eva khalv imāni bhūtāni jāyante |\nānandena jātāni jīvanti | ānandaṃ prayanty abhisaṃviśantīti ||3.6.1||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "आनन्दः ब्रह्म",
          "meaning": "bliss is Brahman"
        },
        {
          "word": "आनन्दात् जायन्ते",
          "meaning": "are born from bliss"
        },
        {
          "word": "आनन्देन जीवन्ति",
          "meaning": "live by bliss"
        },
        {
          "word": "आनन्दम् प्रयन्ति",
          "meaning": "return into bliss"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "He knew: Bliss is Brahman. For from bliss alone are all these beings born; by bliss they live once born; into bliss they return at death.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "आनन्दः — परमानन्दः — ब्रह्मैव। सर्वाणि भूतानि आनन्दात् जायन्ते — ब्रह्मण एव उत्पद्यन्ते।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: Bliss is Brahman itself. All beings are born from Brahman-bliss, sustained by it, and return to it. This is Bhrigu's final realization after progressive inquiry — the ultimate ground is pure bliss (ananda)."
    },
